label chapter9:

    # [Scene: Train Unloading at Pier | Morning]

    scene bg ch13_4001e7_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, buoyant strings with a steady rhythmic pluck]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant clank of metal on wood, excited murmur of many voices, the hollow thunk of crates hitting ramps]
    "You are here because you chose to scale. The signature on the open-source repository glows on your tablet like a pact: not just a file, but a promise extended beyond Mariner's Reach. You signed your name and a dozen others, and trains began to arrive."
    "The first crate opens nearby with a smell that makes you laugh—fresh coffee, beans from a town three stations up that has been following your posts. Someone shouts in a language you only half-recognize; a volunteer"
    "with a bright scarf waves and grins, lifting a solar panel like a trophy. It feels, absurdly and perfectly, like a festival."
    "You move through the crowd with your notebook tablet balanced against your hip, thumbed notes and schematics flicking by. You keep doing the work that has always steadied you—checking measurements, matching manifests, nudging teams to orient"
    "panels so they catch the best angle. Kai Nakamura is there, camera slung low at his hip, already capturing the light in frames that make even a pallet of bolts look pilgrimage-worthy."
    "Tom is at the fore of a small group, demonstrating a joint technique with the blunt, patient authority that has made his hands as trustworthy as the shop they belong to. There is sawdust in his beard and a grin that refuses to be small."
    show tomas_tom_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_tom_alvarez "No, no—slow your pull there. Let the seam seat. You can't rush patience the way you rush a rope."
    "Volunteer: (laughing) 'Yes, Tom. Teach us patience, master.'"
    "Tom: (to you, in a quieter tone) 'Feels good, seeing these kids come through. Your name's on this as much as anyone's, Iris.'"
    "You feel the chord of something warm press against the hollow of your ribs—pride threaded with the old ache of responsibility. This is what you wanted: repair that invites hands, knowledge that opens rather than closes."
    "You had feared that scaling would dilute the town's character. Instead, it is rewriting it with new script: visitors learn your techniques; your people teach theirs."
    "Kai Nakamura steps in beside you, camera pointed mostly at the work but occasionally sliding sideways to catch the way your mouth sets when you're thinking. When he speaks, he keeps his voice low enough that it feels like you're being let in on a joke."
    show kai_nakamura at right:
        zoom 0.7

    kai_nakamura "You know, if we put the panels two degrees further that way, we'll pick up an extra ten percent by noon. I patched the model last night."
    "You glance at his screen, a quick, brilliant overlay of sun angles and tilt vectors. It is the kind of small, precise optimism he gives the world—measurement as affection."
    show iris_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    iris_alvarez "Good. Run with it. Make a quick sheet and pin it to the loading table. I'll let Tom know."
    "Kai Nakamura: (hesitates, then grins) 'Also—I'm doing a short piece on the train crews. Want to say something on camera?'"
    "Your first reaction is to think of guardrails: who speaks for the town, and how their words will open doors—or invite the wrong kind of eyes. Publicity is oxygen and gasoline in the same breath. You"
    "should be cautious. But there's coffee, and crates, and hands, and a palpable change spreading across the pier like warm light."

    iris_alvarez "Keep it focused on the process—how it grows skill and keeps people in work. Not the funding sources."

    kai_nakamura "Got it. No billboard shots. Human frames only."
    "He angles the camera deliberately, and you find yourself offering a line—simple, precise. A sentence that will travel to other towns and, maybe, become a small spur for someone else to start."

    menu:
        "Let Kai record you saying a short line":
            "You step into the frame for a breath and speak about skill-sharing and the slow building of resilience. He smiles, satisfied, and slips the clip into his rolling feed — something candid that will humanize the movement."
        "Ask Kai to save the camera for now":
            "You shake your head, tuck at the braided bracelet on your wrist, and ask him to wait. He nods, understanding the need to control the narrative, and turns his camera back to the panels. The footage will be delayed but purer to your intent."

    menu:
        "Let a volunteer help you catalog incoming blueprints now":
            "You hand over the tablet and watch as someone else tags files with new annotations. It feels good—to let trust be operational. The repository grows thicker with lived detail."
        "Keep cataloging yourself to ensure consistency":
            "You tuck the tablet closer and continue tagging by hand, because consistency matters and mistakes here ripple out. It slows you, but the entries feel certain as you make them."

    menu:
        "Let Kai pitch a short livestream tour of the workshops":
            "You sign off on a five-minute live tour: human faces, tool close-ups, Etta's corner, Tom's bench. The stream draws a modest, engaged audience—comments appear like small hands reaching in, supportive and curious."
        "Hold off on any livestream until we set clear messaging":
            "You ask him to hold the stream and help you draft clear points first. He frowns but understands; the publicity will wait for careful framing. The delay feels responsible, if slower."

    jump chapter6
    return
